@bddppq Hi, I totally agree it is not a good idea. As I explained, the bug does not impact our implementation. On GPU, we use "NCHW" format which will always be translated to CuDNN calls. The complication arises because tensorflow pooling op natively supports either "SAME" padding or "VALID" padding. If the padding is neither "SAME" nor "VALID", then there is no native way to support this kinda of padding. 

In addition, because average pooling op needs to know what paddings are added (because the padded values have to be excluded from the averaging process). Thus using tf.pad is out of question as well. 

However, this usually does not occur (in all 9 model tests, this only occurred in shufflenet) and we will try to use native pooling ops as much as we can before switching to our custom node which can be useful in verifying other parts of the neural net.
